+    \subsection{Derived thin-filament energy scale}
+        \label{subsec:derived_thin_filament_energy_scale}
+
+        \textbf{[DERIVED / LEADING-ORDER FILAMENT LIMIT].}
+        The canon may use a hydrodynamic thin-filament energy scale before any
+        empirical topological screening functional is introduced.  For a slender
+        closed swirl tube with circulation $\Gamma$, physical centerline length
+        $L_{\rm phys}(K)$, core cutoff $\rc$, and outer matching scale
+        $\ell_{\rm out}$, the leading envelope contribution is
+        \begin{align}
+            E_{\rm fil}^{(0)}[K]
+            \simeq
+            \frac{\rhoF\Gamma^2}{4\pi}\,
+            L_{\rm phys}(K)\,
+            \ln\!\left(\frac{\ell_{\rm out}}{\rc}\right)
+            +
+            T_{\rm core}\,L_{\rm phys}(K)
+            +\cdots .
+            \label{eq:canon_thin_filament_energy_scale}
+        \end{align}
+        The first term is the usual slender-vortex logarithmic energy scale,
+        while $T_{\rm core}$ records the resolved line-tension contribution of
+        the core model.
+
+        \textbf{[CANON GUARD].}
+        Equation~\eqref{eq:canon_thin_filament_energy_scale} is the derived
+        length/logarithm anchor for later knot screening.  The surrogate terms
+        in Eq.~\eqref{eq:research_track_energy_normal_form} may be calibrated
+        against this energy scale, but they are not themselves derived by merely
+        being listed as topological descriptors.
+
